      "properties": {"Node name for S&R": "Note"},
      "widgets_values": [
        "BASE SINGER RENDERER — Wan 2.1 + IP-Adapter FaceID (FINAL)\n=========================================\n\nUSE THIS WORKFLOW FOR: final-quality base singer shots\n                          (after LTX prototyping confirmed the shot)\nEXPECTED SPEED: ~12-15 min per 5s clip at 512x512 on RTX 4090 mobile\n\nSAME CONCEPT AS WORKFLOW 01 (LTX) BUT:\n  • Wan 2.1 1.3B GGUF Q5 instead of LTX (better photoreal skin/eyes)\n  • motion_strength set LOW (0.3) — keep face stable for LatentSync\n  • Higher quality but ~30x slower than LTX\n\nWIDGET NOTES (WanImageToVideo):\n- [0,1] width, height = 512, 512\n- [2] length = 81 frames (~3.4s at 25fps)\n- [3] steps = 30\n- [4] cfg = 5.0 (Wan likes higher CFG)\n- [10] motion_strength = 0.3 (LOW — critical for LatentSync)\n- [11] seed\n\nWHY 512x512 INSTEAD OF 832x480?\n  LatentSync works best on square or near-square input because it crops\n  to a face bounding box. 512x512 gives a clean head+shoulders framing\n  that the LatentSync face detector can locate reliably.\n\nWHY LOW MOTION STRENGTH?\n  LatentSync re-renders the mouth region frame-by-frame. If the base video\n  has too much head motion, the face bounding box moves around and the\n  lip-sync becomes unstable. motion_strength=0.3 keeps head motion\n  minimal while still having some life in the shot.\n\n16GB VRAM TIPS:\n  • Wan 1.3B Q5 + IP-Adapter at 512x512: ~14GB peak → tight on 16GB\n  • If OOM: drop IP-Adapter weight to 0.7, or use LTX instead\n  • Don't combine with --cache-none disabled (you need cache off)\n\nPROMPT TIPS:\n  Same as workflow 01 — describe pose/lighting, NOT appearance.\n  Add 'static head pose' to the prompt for even less motion."
      ],
      "color": "#432",
      "bgcolor": "#653"
    }
